Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved, peeled, and thinly sliced). Trim the @carrot{1}(trimmed, quartered lengthways and chopped into 1cm chunks), quarter lengthways and chop into 1cm chunks (no need to peel). Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Drain and rinse the @lentils{1%can} in a #sieve{}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once the pan is hot, add the @British Beef Mince{120%g} and fry until browned, ~{3-5%minutes}. Break it up with a #wooden spoon{} as it cooks. Once browned, add the onion and carrot and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and a pinch of @sugar{pinch}. Fry until the veggies have softened, ~{6-7%minutes}.

While the veg softens cut the @Ciabatta{2} in half as though you're making a sandwich. Pop them on a #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{} and sprinkle on the @Sumac{1}. Set aside.

Add the garlic, @Harissa Paste{25%g} and @Ras-el-Hanout{1/2%tsp} to the beef (add slightly less paste and spice if you don't like too much heat). Stir and cook for ~{1%minute}. Pour in the @chopped tomatoes{1}(diced), lentils and @Water for the Beef{150%ml}. Stir in the @Beef Stock Powder{1} to dissolve, bring the mixture to the boil. Lower the heat and simmer until thickened, ~{6-8%minutes}.

> TIP: Add a splash of water if the harira is a little thick so you can dip your bread in it!

Meanwhile, pop the ciabatta into your #oven{} to bake until golden, ~{4-5%minutes}. Slice the @Olives{30}(sliced) and set aside. When the harira is cooked, taste and add salt and pepper if you feel it needs it.

Halve the ciabatta into triangles. Spoon the harira into #bowls{} and top with a spoonful of @Greek Style Natural Yoghurt{75%g}, some @black pepper{} and some olive slices. Enjoy!